31 SECTION 3.(j) G.S. 90-178.6 reads as rewritten:
32 "§ 90-178.6. Denial, revocation or suspension of approval.
33 (a) In accordance with the provisions of Chapter 150B, the joint subcommittee North
34 Carolina Board of Nursing may deny, revoke or suspend approval when a person has:
35 (1) Failed to satisfy the qualifications for approval;approval.
36 (2) Failed to pay the annual renewal fee by January 1 of the current year;year.
37 (3) Given false information or withheld material information in applying for
38 approval;approval.
39 (4) Demonstrated incompetence in the practice of midwifery;midwifery.
40 (5) Violated any of the provisions of this Article;Article.
41 (6) A mental or physical disability or uses any drug to a degree that interferes with
42 his or her fitness to practice midwifery;midwifery.
43 (7) Engaged in conduct that endangers the public health;health.
44 (8) Engaged in conduct that deceives, defrauds, or harms the public in the course
45 of professional activities or services; orservices.
46 (9) Been convicted of or pleaded guilty or nolo contendere to any felony under
47 the laws of the United States or of any state of the United States indicating
48 professional unfitness.
49 (b) Revocation or suspension of a license to practice nursing pursuant to G.S. 90-171.37
50 shall automatically result in comparable action against the person's approval to practice
51 midwifery under this Article."
Page 10 Senate Bill 345-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 3.(k) G.S. 90-178.7 reads as rewritten:
2 "§ 90-178.7. Enforcement.
3 (a) The joint subcommittee North Carolina Board of Nursing may apply to the Superior
4 Court of Wake County to restrain any violation of this Article.
5 (b) No person shall perform any act constituting the practice of midwifery, as defined in
6 this Article, or any of the branches thereof, unless the person shall have been first approved under
7 this Article. Any person who practices midwifery without being duly approved and registered,
8 as provided in this Article, shall not be allowed to maintain any action to collect any fee for such
9 services. Any person so practicing without being duly approved shall be guilty of a Class 3
10 misdemeanor. Any person so practicing without being duly approved under this Article and who
11 is falsely representing himself or herself in a manner as being approved under this Article or any
12 Article of this Chapter shall be guilty of a Class I felony."
13 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 90-2 reads as rewritten:
14 "§ 90-2. Medical Board.
15 (a) There is established the North Carolina Medical Board to regulate the practice of
16 medicine and surgery for the benefit and protection of the people of North Carolina. The Board
17 shall consist of 13 members:
18 (1) Six of the members shall be duly licensed physicians recommended by the
19 Review Panel and appointed by the Governor as set forth in G.S. 90-3.
20 (2) Five members shall all be appointed by the Governor as follows:
21 a. One shall be a member of The Old North State Medical Society. This
22 Board position shall be subject to recommendations of the Review
23 Panel pursuant to G.S. 90-3.
24 b. One shall be a public member, and this Board position shall not be
25 subject to recommendation of the Review Panel pursuant to G.S. 90-3.
26 c. One Two shall be a physician assistant assistants as defined in
27 G.S. 90-18.1 as recommended by the Review Panel pursuant to
28 G.S. 90-3.
29 d. One shall be a nurse practitioner as defined in G.S. 90-18.2 as
30 recommended by the Review Panel pursuant to G.S. 90-3.
31 e. One shall be a duly licensed physician who is a doctor of osteopathic
32 medicine or a full-time faculty member of one of the medical schools
33 in North Carolina who utilizes integrative medicine in that person's
34 clinical practice, as recommended by the Review Panel pursuant to
35 G.S. 90-3.
36 (3) Two public members appointed by the General Assembly in accordance with
37 G.S. 120-121, one upon recommendation of the Speaker of the House of
38 Representatives and one upon the recommendation of the President Pro
39 Tempore of the Senate.
40 (a1) Each appointing and nominating authority shall endeavor to see, insofar as possible,
41 that its appointees and nominees to the Board reflect the composition of the State with regard to
42 gender, ethnic, racial, and age composition.
43 (b) No member shall serve more than two complete three-year terms in a lifetime, except
44 that each member shall serve until a successor is chosen and qualifies.
45 (b1) A public member appointed pursuant to sub-subdivision (a)(2)b. and subdivision
46 (a)(3) of this section shall not be a health care provider nor the spouse of a health care provider.
47 For the purpose of Board membership, "health care provider" means any licensed health care
48 professional, agent, or employee of a health care institution, health care insurer, health care
49 professional school, or a member of any allied health profession. For purposes of this section, a
50 person enrolled in a program as preparation to be a licensed health care professional or an allied
Senate Bill 345-Second Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 health professional shall be deemed a health care provider. For purposes of this section, any
2 person with significant financial interest in a health service or profession is not a public member.
3 (c) Repealed by Session Laws 2003-366, s. 1, effective October 1, 2003.
4 (d) Any member of the Board may be removed from office by the Governor for good
5 cause shown. Any vacancy in the physician, physician assistant, or nurse practitioner physician
6 or physician assistant membership of the Board shall be filled for the period of the unexpired
7 term by the Governor from a list submitted by the Review Panel pursuant to G.S. 90-3. Any
8 vacancy in the public membership of the Board shall be filled by the appropriate appointing
9 authority for the unexpired term.
10 (e) The North Carolina Medical Board shall have the power to acquire, hold, rent,
11 encumber, alienate, and otherwise deal with real property in the same manner as any private
12 person or corporation, subject only to approval of the Governor and the Council of State as to the
13 acquisition, rental, encumbering, leasing, and sale of real property. Collateral pledged by the
14 Board for an encumbrance is limited to the assets, income, and revenues of the Board."
15 SECTION 4.(b) G.S. 90-3 reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 90-3. Review Panel recommends certain Board members; criteria for recommendations.
17 (a) There is created a Review Panel to review all applicants for the physician positions,
18 the physician assistant position, and the nurse practitioner position and physician assistant
19 positions on the Board. The Review Panel shall consist of nine members, including four from the
20 Medical Society, one from the Old North State Medical Society, one from the North Carolina
21 Osteopathic Medical Association, one two from the North Carolina Academy of Physician
22 Assistants, one from the North Carolina Nurses Association Council of Nurse Practitioners, and
23 one public member currently serving or who has served on the Board. Each member shall serve
24 for a term of three years, ending December 31 of the last year of the term. No member shall serve
25 more than two terms. All physicians, physician assistants, and nurse practitioners physicians and
26 physician assistants serving on the Review Panel shall be actively practicing in North Carolina.
27 The Review Panel shall contract for the independent administrative services needed to
28 complete its functions and duties. The Board shall provide funds to pay the reasonable cost for
29 the administrative services of the Review Panel. The Board shall convene the initial meeting of
30 the Review Panel. The Review Panel shall elect a chair, and all subsequent meetings shall be
31 convened by the Review Panel.
32 The Governor shall appoint Board members as provided in G.S. 90-2. The Review Panel shall
33 attempt to make its recommendations to the Governor reflect the composition of the State with
34 regard to gender, ethnic, racial, medical specialty, and age.
35 The Review Panel and its members and staff shall not be held liable in any civil or criminal
36 proceeding for exercising, in good faith, the powers and duties authorized by law.
37 (b) To be considered qualified for a physician position, the physician assistant position,
38 or nurse practitioner or physician assistant position on the Board, an applicant shall meet each of
39 the following criteria:
40 (1) Hold an active, nonlimited license to practice medicine in North Carolina, or
41 in the case of a physician assistant and nurse practitioner, assistant, hold an
42 active license or approval to perform medical acts, tasks, and functions in
43 North Carolina.
44 (2) Have an active clinical or teaching practice. For purposes of this subdivision,
45 the term "active" means patient care, or instruction of students in an accredited
46 medical school or residency, or clinical research program, for 20 hours or
47 more per week.
48 (3) Have actively practiced in this State for at least five consecutive years
49 immediately preceding the appointment.
50 (4) Intend to remain in active practice in this State for the duration of the term on
51 the Board.
Page 12 Senate Bill 345-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) Submit at least three letters of recommendation, either from individuals or
2 from professional or other societies or organizations.
3 (6) Have no public disciplinary history with the Board or any other licensing
4 board in this State or another state over the past 10 years before applying for
5 appointment to the Board.
6 (7) Have no history of felony convictions of any kind.
7 (8) Have no misdemeanor convictions related to the practice of medicine.
8 (9) Indicate, in a manner prescribed by the Review Panel, that the applicant: (i)
9 understands that the primary purpose of the Board is to protect the public; (ii)
10 is willing to take appropriate disciplinary action against his or her peers for
11 misconduct or violations of the standards of medical care; and (iii) is aware of
12 the time commitment needed to be a constructive member of the Board.
13 (10) Have not served more than 72 months as a member of the Board.
14 (c) The Review Panel shall recommend at least two qualified nominees for each open
15 position on the Board. If the Governor chooses not to appoint either of the recommended
16 nominees, the Review Panel shall recommend at least two new qualified nominees.
17 (d) Notice of open physician, physician assistant, or nurse practitioner physician or
18 physician assistant positions on the Board shall be sent to all physicians currently licensed to
19 practice medicine in North Carolina and all physician assistants and nurse practitioners currently
20 licensed or approved to perform medical acts, tasks, and functions in this State.
21 (e) Applicants for positions on the Board shall not be required to be members of any
22 professional association or society, except as provided in G.S. 90-2(a)(2)a.
23 (f) Notwithstanding any provision of G.S. 90-16, the Board may provide confidential and
24 nonpublic licensing and investigative information in its possession to the Review Panel regarding
25 applicants.
26 (g) All applications, records, papers, files, reports, and all investigative and licensing
27 information received by the Review Panel from the Board and other documents received or
28 gathered by the Review Panel, its members, employees, agents, and consultants as a result of
29 soliciting, receiving, and reviewing applications and making recommendations as required in this
30 section shall not be considered public records within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General
31 Statutes. All such information shall be privileged, confidential, and not subject to discovery,
32 subpoena, or other means of legal compulsion for release to any person other than the Review
33 Panel, the Board, and their employees, agents, or consultants, except as provided in this section.
34 The Review Panel shall publish on its Internet Web site the names and practice addresses of all
35 applicants within 10 days after the application deadline. The Review Panel shall publish on its
36 Internet Web site the names and practice addresses of the nominees recommended to the
37 Governor within 10 days after notifying the Governor of those recommendations and not less
38 than 30 days prior to the expiration of the open position on the Board.
39 (h) The Review Panel is a public body within the meaning of Article 33C of Chapter 143
40 of the General Statutes. In addition to the provisions contained in Article 33C of Chapter 143 of
41 the General Statutes permitting a public body to conduct business in a closed session, the Review
42 Panel shall meet in closed session to review applications; interview applicants; review and
43 discuss information received from the Board; and discuss, debate, and vote on recommendations
44 to the Governor."
45 SECTION 5. The North Carolina Board of Nursing shall adopt rules to implement
46 the provisions of Section 3 of this act.
47 SECTION 6. Section 1 of this act becomes effective when the North Carolina
48 Medical Board adopts the permanent rules required under Section 2 of this act or June 30, 2026,
49 whichever occurs first. The North Carolina Medical Board shall notify the Revisor of Statutes
50 when the rules required under Section 2 of this act have been adopted. Section 3 of this act
51 becomes effective when the North Carolina Board of Nursing adopts the permanent rules
Senate Bill 345-Second Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 required under Section 5 of this act or June 30, 2026, whichever occurs first. The North Carolina
2 Board of Nursing shall notify the Revisor of Statutes when the rules required under Section 5 of
3 this act have been adopted. The remainder of this act is effective when it becomes law.
